[1] Spain (Alicante)
Date: 14 Jun 2011
Source: Informacion.com [in Spanish, machine trans. abridged,
edited]
http://www.diarioinformacion.com/elche/2011/06/14/sanidad-detecta-brote-sarampion-alicante/1138129.html


Two new cases of measles in one-year-old infants were added yesterday
[13 Jun 2011] to the outbreak that occurred last week at a nursery
school in Alicante affecting 6 children under 15 months of age.

The Department of Health has diagnosed so far this year [2011] 14
cases of this disease, which WHO had expected to have eradicated in
2005, but which has recurred now in Spain and more especially in some
other European countries, such as France, where this year [2011] there
have been at least 5000 cases, with 3000 of them in March 2011 alone.

Although the virus has only now arrived in this autonomous territory,
the situation is worrisome, said a spokesman for the Department of
Epidemiology, who stated that 14 diagnosed cases have occurred in 2
areas, Alcoy and Alicante, and that the disease has affected 2
unconnected groups. Measles virus infection has spread to 8 young
people between 18 and 20 years of age who had received only one dose
of vaccine and, as a result, are less protected against the pathogen.

In Alicante, epidemiologists are looking for the index case, who is
thought to have brought the virus from another neighbouring autonomous
region. The Department of Health will advance the administration of
MMR (measles, mumps and rubella) vaccination to 12 months instead of
the current 15 months.

--
