[9] USA (Massachusetts)
Date: Tue 14 Jun 2011
Source: Westborough Patch [edited]
http://westborough.patch.com/articles/measles-testing-inclusive-cdc-now-involved


State lab results on a possible case of measles in Westborough are
inconclusive, Paul McNulty told Westborough Patch. "They will be
sending the results to the CDC (Centers for Disease Control) in
Atlanta for interpretation," said McNulty, Westborough director of
public health. "This is an unusual situation."

An employee of the Bose Corporation at 9 Technology Dr. in
Westborough reportedly showed signs of the disease around Wed 1 Jun
2011. McNulty explained that when a doctor suspects a case of measles,
it is reported to the state, which is what happened in this case. The
state then notifies the local board of health. "The incubation period
for measles is about 14 days, so we're just about there," McNulty
said.

Despite inconclusive results, Bose will be holding a vaccination
clinic for its employees, McNulty said. The clinic will offer 300
doses of the MMR (measles, mumps, and rubella) vaccine. The vaccine is
sent to the Board of Health office in Westborough from a state lab in
Jamaica Plain and will be delivered to the Westborough location of
Bose.

"I recommend they get the shot," said McNulty when asked what he
advises for the employees of Bose. He did not recommend the general
public seek the vaccination because of this incident. The vaccination
is commonly given to children in 2 doses by age 6. CDC recommends that
anyone 18 or older who was born after 1956 get at least one dose of
the MMR vaccine unless they can show that they have had either the
vaccines or the diseases.

The agency does not advise the vaccine for people who have ever had a
life-threatening allergic reaction to gelatin, the antibiotic neomysin
or to a previous dose of the MMR vaccine. Those who are ill and
pregnant women should also wait to get the vaccine. CDC recommends
that patients with HIV/AIDS, a disease that affects the immune system,
cancer, or a low platelet count consult a doctor before getting the
MMR vaccine.

--
