[11] Australia (Western)
Date: Sat 18 Jun 2011
Source: Pilbaraecho, Karratha News [edited]
http://pilbaraecho.com.au/?p=516


The Department of Health is alerting the public to an increased risk
of measles cases in WA [Western Australia], following the
identification of 4 cases in early June 2011. The warning comes after
one adult returned from the Philippines with the disease, and an
unvaccinated child was infected in Thailand and then passed the
infection to his 2 younger unvaccinated siblings.

Director of communicable disease control Dr Paul Armstrong said a
large number of people were potentially exposed to infection at
several locations, including the emergency departments of Joondalup
and Princess Margaret hospitals, at north metropolitan general
practice surgeries where the infected cases were seen, and at schools
and clubs the cases attended while infectious. "As a result, public
health staff has [sic] been contacting exposed individuals who may be
at risk and providing advice," he said.

Measles is contagious for up to 5 days before the development of the
rash and for 4 days after it starts, and both children and adults who
have been unwittingly exposed are at risk of developing measles if
they are not immune.

"A person is considered immune to measles if they have received 2
doses of the measles mumps rubella (MMR) vaccine or were born before
1966," he said. "Individuals who may have been exposed and who develop
a fever and cough or runny nose in the next 2 weeks should stay at
home and promptly consult their doctor. The patient should mention
their possible contact with measles when they call so they can be
isolated when they arrive at the surgery and prevent the potential
spread of measles to other patients."

Measles is a highly contagious viral illness that can cause serious
disease. Early symptoms include fever, cough, runny nose and sore eyes
followed by a red blotchy rash about 3 days later. Naturally occurring
measles has been eliminated from WA for over a decade, but occasional
cases and small outbreaks occur associated with tourists or WA
residents returning from overseas.

Complications following measles can be very serious and may include
ear infections and pneumonia in about 10 per cent of cases. Around 50
per cent of cases may require hospitalisation, and about one person in
every 1000 will develop encephalitis, an inflammation of the brain.

